into the country itself, up to
100 miles from

29:24.162 --> 29:25.931 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
the border.

29:25.964 --> 29:31.670 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Within that zone, its agents can
stop, detain
and search any person if an
agent suspects

29:31.703 --> 29:33.672 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
a crime is being committed.

29:33.705 --> 29:36.808 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
About two-thirds of Americans
live under Border
Patrol's authority.

29:36.842 --> 29:41.146 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But, in practice, it's the
people along the
border who are impacted most
directly.

29:41.179 --> 29:44.716 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
VICENTE PACO, Spokesman, Border
Patrol: Every
major route of egress into the
United States

29:44.750 --> 29:46.818 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
along the border is going to
have one of those
checkpoints.

29:46.852 --> 29:51.323 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Border Patrol
spokesman
Vicente Paco grew up in a border
town himself.

29:51.356 --> 29:55.127 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He took us on a tour of the
border near Nogales,
Arizona.

29:55.160 --> 29:59.398 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
What would you say to people in
these neighboring
communities who appreciate what
your mission

29:59.431 --> 30:04.169 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
is and the job you're tasked
with, but they
still say that the impact on
their community

30:04.202 --> 30:05.470 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
is too much?

30:05.504 --> 30:07.439 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
VICENTE PACO: I like to say that
I'm a community
member myself.

30:07.472 --> 30:09.408 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I grew up in a border town.

30:09.441 --> 30:16.314 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I saw how illegal activity
affects people
that I went to high school with.

30:16.348 --> 30:20.786 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
People that I grew up with ended
up in jail
because they were recruited by
transnational

30:20.819 --> 30:24.122 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
criminal organizations to bring
illicit cargo
across the border.

30:24.156 --> 30:28.627 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SCOTT RAFTERY, Rancher: The
border check stations
can be bothersome if you have to
drive through

30:28.660 --> 30:30.662 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
them every day.

30:30.696 --> 30:33.465 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They stop you, they hold you up
for a little
bit.

30:33.498 --> 30:37.035 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But I think, overall, they're a
necessary
evil.

30:37.069 --> 30:41.373 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Scott Raftery
is a rancher
and horse trainer near Arivaca.

30:41.406 --> 30:46.244 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
He says he's recovered a
half-dozen dead bodies
from the land he works.

30:46.278 --> 30:51.450 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He once came home to an armed
standoff between
border agents and border
crossers on his own

30:51.483 --> 30:53.185 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
property.

30:53.218 --> 30:56.154 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SCOTT RAFTERY: There's people
out there crossing
our borders undetected,
unstopped.

30:56.188 --> 30:59.958 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And, somewhere, we have to hold
the line on
them.

30:59.991 --> 31:05.831 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And if it's not at the border,
it's somewhere
close to border, because, once
they get north

31:05.864 --> 31:07.599 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
of here, they're gone.

31:07.632 --> 31:12.504 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Three hundred
miles away
in Yuma, Arizona, Sheriff Leon
Wilmot also

31:12.537 --> 31:14.639 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
supports stronger security.

31:14.673 --> 31:19.544 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The former Marine has spent 32
years in the
sheriff's department, and today
works closely

31:19.578 --> 31:24.916 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
with federal agencies like
Customs and Border
Protection, Immigration, Drug
Enforcement,

31:24.950 --> 31:30.589 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
even the FBI, all to fight crime
in his city
of 90,000 residents.

31:30.622 --> 31:35.761 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
He says the hassle of
checkpoints and an increased
police presence is a small price
to pay to

31:35.794 --> 31:37.529 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
protect residents' safety.

31:37.562 --> 31:40.665 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
LEON WILMOT, Yuma County
Sheriff: If you live
on the border, you have to
understand that

31:40.699 --> 31:43.802 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
you're going to have to deal
with one issue
or the other.

31:43.835 --> 31:46.404 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Which one makes more sense?

31:46.438 --> 31:49.474 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Public safety, to me, is the
government's
priority.

31:49.508 --> 31:54.246 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
To me, that's a no-brainer, or
if it's going
to prevent somebody from being
the victim

31:54.279 --> 31:55.981 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
of a homicide.

31:56.014 --> 32:01.153 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
If we can do something to deter
folks from
dying and keep those illegal
drugs out of

32:01.186 --> 32:02.854 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
our country, to me, that makes
sense.

32:02.888 --> 32:04.990 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: And for those
caught in
the dragnet?

32:05.023 --> 32:09.361 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LEON WILMOT: If you're abiding
by the law,
then you have nothing to worry
about.

32:09.394 --> 32:12.597 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
If you got a ticket, that's
because you broke
the law.

32:12.631 --> 32:16.668 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: But it's not
so easy for
Esteban Duarte.

32:16.701 --> 32:20.472 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He lives in Yuma with his kids,
and he's a
substance abuse counselor.

32:20.505 --> 32:25.610 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He says, every time he goes
through a checkpoint,
he ends up in what's called
secondary, where

32:25.644 --> 32:27.546 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
you're subject to being held and
searched.

32:27.579 --> 32:29.281 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ESTEBAN DUARTE, Substance Abuse
Counselor:
They do ask me for documents.

32:29.314 --> 32:31.650 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They keep me sitting in a room
for a while.

32:31.683 --> 32:34.186 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And they just -- sometimes,
they're really
rude.

32:34.219 --> 32:38.356 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They tell you to open your car,
run you like
a little dog.

32:38.390 --> 32:41.927 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Either you sit, or I'm going to
smack you.

32:41.960 --> 32:45.931 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Richard Edgar,
who is a
defense attorney in Yuma, sees
this frequently.

32:45.964 --> 32:49.868 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
RICHARD EDGAR, Defense Attorney:
You talk
to a federal agent 100 percent
of the time

32:49.901 --> 32:51.703 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
when you want to leave Yuma
County.

32:51.736 --> 32:54.873 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You're going to be talking to
him, answering
questions about your
citizenship.

32:54.906 --> 32:57.342 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You're going to be answering
questions about
where you're going.

32:57.375 --> 33:00.145 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They have the authority at any
point in time
to put you into secondary.

33:00.178 --> 33:02.747 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And, in secondary, that's where
they really
get into it.

33:02.781 --> 33:06.785 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Edgar says 80
percent of
his cases are drug-related
offenses from the

33:06.818 --> 33:08.620 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
nearby checkpoints.

33:08.653 --> 33:13.725 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
A 2013 report by the Center for
Investigative
Reporting found that Border
Patrol around

33:13.758 --> 33:19.631 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Yuma had some of the highest
rates of arrests,
not for human trafficking or
immigration violations,

33:19.664 --> 33:22.000 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
but for possession of small
amounts of marijuana.

33:22.033 --> 33:26.238 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
RICHARD EDGAR: But if you drive
by those checkpoints
as many times as somebody down
here does,

33:26.271 --> 33:30.408 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
you're going to see cars on the
side in secondary
being ripped apart.

33:30.442 --> 33:34.746 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Now, if they find drugs in 10
percent of those,
is it worth it?

33:34.779 --> 33:38.049 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Esteban Duarte
isn't sure.

33:38.083 --> 33:42.554 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He says of course he wants his
community and
his kids to be safe from crime.

33:42.587 --> 33:46.458 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But he worries that the hand of
Border Patrol
comes down too hard.

33:46.491 --> 33:51.696 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ESTEBAN DUARTE: From a father's
perspective,
I don't want anything going on,
on the streets

33:51.730 --> 33:55.100 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
that's going to harm my family.

33:55.133 --> 34:02.807 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
, But on the other point of
view, I could
look at it as, why did they
label me for?

34:02.841 --> 34:08.446 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Americans
living along the
border will likely experience
even more scrutiny,

34:08.480 --> 34:13.752 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
as the Trump administration
orders an additional
5,000 Border Patrol agents.

34:13.785 --> 34:18.056 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
For the "PBS NewsHour" I'm
William Brangham
in Yuma, Arizona.

34:18.089 --> 34:21.793 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And we have more
from our trip
to the border online.

34:21.826 --> 34:28.166 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We visit a soup kitchen for
recently deported
migrants in Mexico near Nogales,
Arizona,

34:28.199 --> 34:33.038 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
where we talked to a husband and
father who
has tried to cross the border
into the U.S.

34:33.071 --> 34:38.243 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
several times.

34:38.276 --> 34:47.886 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now: a Supreme Court ruling that
could have
a significant impact on special
education

34:47.919 --> 34:50.355 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
in schools around the U.S.

34:50.388 --> 34:55.360 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
John Yang is back with that
story for our
weekly education segment, Making
the Grade.

34:55.393 --> 35:01.099 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: Amid all of the big
news last week,
this stunning ruling may have
been overlooked.

35:01.132 --> 35:05.470 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The court unanimously ruled that
schools must
give students with disabilities
the chance

35:05.503 --> 35:09.841 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
to make meaningful and
appropriately ambitious
progress.

35:09.874 --> 35:14.546 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That could set the bar higher
for more than
six million students nationwide.

35:14.579 --> 35:18.950 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Lisa Stark of our partner
Education Week has
been covering this story and
joins me now.

35:18.984 --> 35:20.018 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Lisa, thanks for being here.

35:20.051 --> 35:21.019 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
LISA STARK, Education Week:
Thanks, John.

35:21.052 --> 35:22.787 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JOHN YANG: What was this case
about?

35:22.821 --> 35:26.958 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LISA STARK: Well, the heart of
this case is
really, what educational benefit
do schools

35:26.992 --> 35:29.227 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
need to provide to these
students.

35:29.260 --> 35:31.963 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's a case out of Colorado,
involved a boy
named Drew.

35:31.997 --> 35:33.531 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
He has autism.

35:33.565 --> 35:35.300 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
The case was filed when he was
10.

35:35.333 --> 35:37.202 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
He's now 17.

35:37.235 --> 35:40.705 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
His parents pulled him out of
the fourth grade
in the Douglas County Public
Schools -- that's

35:40.739 --> 35:43.641 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
right outside Denver -- because
they were
concerned.

35:43.675 --> 35:45.810 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
His behavior was deteriorating.

35:45.844 --> 35:51.216 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And they also felt that he
wasn't really getting
any educational benefit, as
required by law.

35:51.249 --> 35:54.819 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They put him in a private school
for autistic
kids, and then they sued the
district.

35:54.853 --> 35:58.790 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And they said, look, if you're
not providing
the appropriate education, you
need to pay

35:58.823 --> 36:00.091 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
for this private school.

36:00.125 --> 36:03.194 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Well, the lower courts all ruled
against the
family.

36:03.228 --> 36:08.299 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, in fact, the 10th Circuit
ruled, the
appeals court ruled that that
school district

36:08.333 --> 36:13.071 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
only had to provide something
that was merely
more than de minimis, in other
words, a very

36:13.104 --> 36:15.373 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
trivial benefit to the child.

36:15.407 --> 36:18.676 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The Supreme Court, as you
indicated, totally
rejected that.

36:18.710 --> 36:20.445 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It was a unanimous decision.

36:20.478 --> 36:26.117 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The court ruled 8-0 that, in
fact, education
programs must be appropriately
ambitious,

36:26.151 --> 36:29.621 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
in light of each child's
circumstance, and
they must be challenged.

36:29.654 --> 36:31.289 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
The kids have to have
challenging objectives.

36:31.322 --> 36:33.758 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOHN YANG: So, what does that
mean for the
classroom?

36:33.792 --> 36:35.693 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
LISA STARK: Depends on the
student.

36:35.727 --> 36:40.899 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
If you're a student who is in a
regular classroom,
maybe you have ADHD, you have a
minor learning

36:40.932 --> 36:44.402 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
disability, you're with every
other student,
it means that you need the
supports to be

36:44.436 --> 36:49.340 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
able to pass that classroom,
that classroom
and that grade, and move on with
your fellow

36:49.374 --> 36:51.242 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
students.

36:51.276 --> 36:54.979 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
If you are a more challenged
student, like
Drew, who has autism, and might
be in a special-ed

36:55.013 --> 36:58.583 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
class, well, then that program
is tailored
to what you can accomplish.

36:58.616 --> 37:02.654 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But, again, as you say, it must
be meaningful
progress, challenging progress.

37:02.687 --> 37:05.657 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
JOHN YANG: And what are
disability advocates
saying about this ruling?

37:05.690 --> 37:07.492 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
LISA STARK: Well, they are
applauding this.

37:07.525 --> 37:12.697 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They see it as a big win for
disability, for
these kids, these nearly seven
million kids,

37:12.730 --> 37:14.299 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
as you said.

37:14.332 --> 37:17.235 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
They do think it's a
game-changer, that it
raises the bar.

37:17.268 --> 37:21.206 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The attorney for the family,
Jack Robinson,
told me that, for the first
time, there's

37:21.239 --> 37:26.644 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
a national standard that
determines really
what is the educational benefit
these kids

37:26.678 --> 37:28.413 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
need?

37:28.446 --> 37:31.382 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And drew's mom, Jennifer, she
told me that
she hopes school districts will
work more

37:31.416 --> 37:36.855 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
closely now with parents, will
be more willing
to do something that is right
for their children.

37:36.888 --> 37:41.126 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Also, we should say that these
advocates think
this is just going to empower
parents, that

37:41.159 --> 37:44.329 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
it gives them more leverage to
demand more
from school districts.

37:44.362 --> 37:45.897 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JOHN YANG: How are the districts
reacting?

37:45.930 --> 37:48.366 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
LISA STARK: Well, they say this
isn't a game-changer.

37:48.399 --> 37:53.671 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They believe that most districts
are already
providing a very good education
for these

37:53.705 --> 37:54.973 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
students with disabilities.

37:55.006 --> 37:58.143 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They say that they meet this
higher standard.

37:58.176 --> 38:00.145 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I did talk to Sue Pudelski.

38:00.178 --> 38:04.449 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And she is with the School
Superintendents
Association.

38:04.482 --> 38:08.853 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
She did tell me that this may
hold districts'
feet to the fire a little bit
more, that they're

38:08.887 --> 38:13.191 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
going to have to justify these
plans they
set out for all of these
students, what is

38:13.224 --> 38:15.293 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
called an IEP.

38:15.326 --> 38:19.164 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
She said, so that may give
parents a little
wherewithal to come in and say,
what's this

38:19.197 --> 38:20.965 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
program and how is it working?

38:20.999 --> 38:25.637 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: And for parents of
children like
Drew, with this ruling, what do
they need

38:25.670 --> 38:27.572 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
to know?

38:27.605 --> 38:30.074 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
LISA STARK: Well, as I
mentioned, every district
needs to set up what is called
an IEP -- it's

38:30.108 --> 38:33.811 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
an individualized education
program -- for
each of these students.

38:33.845 --> 38:35.480 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And parents have to sign off on
this.

38:35.513 --> 38:37.782 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And, in fact, that's happening
right now.

38:37.815 --> 38:41.252 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, this is sort of fortuitous
timing, if
you will, because these are set
up in the

38:41.286 --> 38:43.454 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
spring for the next school year.

38:43.488 --> 38:47.292 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Parents have always been told,
pay careful
attention, see what the district
is going

38:47.325 --> 38:50.962 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to do, ask a lot of questions,
find out what
resources you're getting.

38:50.995 --> 38:54.899 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now they can also walk in with
this Supreme
Court decision and say, hey,
here are the

38:54.933 --> 38:56.734 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
standards that you need to meet
for my child.

38:56.768 --> 39:02.640 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
JOHN YANG: Lisa Stark of
Education Week, great
to see you again.

39:02.674 --> 39:09.013 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
LISA STARK: Thank you.

39:09.047 --> 39:17.255 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: It was on a visit
to the huge
refugee camp at Zaatari in
Jordan today that

39:17.288 --> 39:23.728 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
U.N. Secretary-General Antonio
Guterres called
for more international support
for Syrian

39:23.761 --> 39:26.297 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
refugees and for the countries
hosting them.

39:26.331 --> 39:32.403 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
To the north of Syria, Turkey
now hosts 3.5
million Syrian refugees.

39:32.437 --> 39:38.810 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
President Erdogan there says
70,000 people
with special talents will be
granted citizenship.

39:38.843 --> 39:44.249 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But a Turkish charity is urging
the government
to grant citizenship to all
refugees, to stop

39:44.282 --> 39:49.988 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
exploitation, and to prevent
violence erupting
between Turks and Syrians.

39:50.021 --> 39:54.058 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Special correspondent Malcolm
Brabant reports
from Western Turkey.

39:54.092 --> 39:59.697 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MALCOLM BRABANT: The Hajeeras
from Northeastern
Syria are creating a new shelter
after being

39:59.731 --> 40:02.533 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
evicted from their tent by
paramilitary police.

40:02.567 --> 40:06.437 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They live with the constant
worry of being
moved on again.

40:06.471 --> 40:12.410 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Aid workers say raids on
unofficial refugee
camps are part of the strategy
to stop migrants

40:12.443 --> 40:14.846 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
from reaching Europe.

40:14.879 --> 40:20.051 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
In an attempt to avoid
discovery, these people
are staying out of sight in
semi-derelict

40:20.084 --> 40:22.754 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
farm buildings.

40:22.787 --> 40:26.658 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
This rough farmland was home to
about 300
refugees for the winter.

40:26.691 --> 40:32.330 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But the Syrians were cleared out
and told
to find accommodation in hotels,
houses or

40:32.363 --> 40:34.132 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
apartments.

40:34.165 --> 40:38.303 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The farmer objected to us
filming, called
the police, and followed us for
several miles

40:38.336 --> 40:41.272 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
as we looked for people willing
to talk.

40:41.306 --> 40:44.876 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MARIAM IBRAHIM, Syrian Refugee
(through translator):
Mariam is my name, Mariam.

40:44.909 --> 40:48.313 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
I'm 30 years old, Mariam
Ibrahim.

40:48.346 --> 40:49.847 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Our life is awful.

40:49.881 --> 40:51.849 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
We have no source of income.

40:51.883 --> 40:52.850 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Nothing.

40:52.884 --> 40:54.686 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Only God is by our side.

40:54.719 --> 40:55.687 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
We have no money.

40:55.720 --> 40:57.121 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
We are on our knees.

40:57.155 --> 40:58.956 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
We're struggling to survive.

40:58.990 --> 41:00.658 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
We just work to live.

41:00.692 --> 41:04.829 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MALCOLM BRABANT: The landowner
is charging
Mariam $100 a month to pitch her
tent.

41:04.862 --> 41:08.366 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
She is alone with her five
children and has
little choice.

41:08.399 --> 41:12.403 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
MARIAM IBRAHIM (through
translator): They
say living in houses is better
for you than

41:12.437 --> 41:13.638 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
living in tents.

41:13.671 --> 41:14.872 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
So, how do we feel?

41:14.906 --> 41:17.208 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I mean, we are crammed on top of
one another.

41:17.241 --> 41:20.878 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I don't have the means or help
or money to
live in a house.

41:20.912 --> 41:24.849 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MALCOLM BRABANT: Despite barely
earning enough
to support her family, Mariam is
trying to

41:24.882 --> 41:30.521 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
send money to Syria for her sick
husband left
behind in an area where Kurdish
forces are

41:30.555 --> 41:34.125 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
fighting Islamic State.

41:34.158 --> 41:36.928 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
There's irregular work in the
fields around
the town of Torbila (ph).

41:36.961 --> 41:38.996 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Here, they're harvesting leeks.

41:39.030 --> 41:44.402 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The Syrians say adults might get
$10 for a
12- to 14-hour day.

41:44.435 --> 41:48.439 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That's about half the statutory
Turkish minimum
wage.

41:48.473 --> 41:50.308 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
The children earn far less.

41:50.341 --> 41:54.545 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
BOY (through translator): In
Syria, they are
all dead or living with death.

41:54.579 --> 41:58.783 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
BOY (through translator): We are
better off
in Turkey compared to Syria.

41:58.816 --> 41:59.784 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
There's no fighting.

41:59.817 --> 42:01.619 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
We are comfortable here.

42:01.652 --> 42:03.688 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
AHMED MOHAMMED KHALAF, Syrian
Refugee (through
translator): I came to Turkey to
work in the

42:03.721 --> 42:05.857 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
orange orchards or flower
fields.

42:05.890 --> 42:08.693 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
The daily pay is low, like 75
cents.

42:08.726 --> 42:13.331 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BOY (through translator): Now we
are working
and coming back from rock
bottom.

42:13.364 --> 42:15.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But I think of being in school
and learning
everything.

42:15.867 --> 42:20.505 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
MALCOLM BRABANT: Refugee
supporters say stories
like this are replicated all
along Turkey's

42:20.538 --> 42:23.975 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Aegean Coast, the gateway to the
Greek Islands.

42:24.008 --> 42:29.414 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The three million Syrians
sheltering in Turkey
are inhabiting a precarious
twilight world

42:29.447 --> 42:34.352 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
where they have no real access
to state services
and are treated like
second-class citizens.

42:34.385 --> 42:40.258 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They may be safe from war, but
they and their
children are exploited and
vulnerable.

42:40.291 --> 42:46.798 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Little wonder that so many of
them wish to
cross this sea to Europe for a
better life.

42:46.831 --> 42:51.302 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
In September 2015, Izmir was
smuggling central.

42:51.335 --> 42:54.972 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
This mosque was full of people
angling to
buy a passage to Europe.

42:55.006 --> 43:00.978 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But after the E.U. signed a $3
billion deal
with Turkey to stem the migrant
flow, the

43:01.012 --> 43:06.017 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
crowds have vanished from the
courtyard, and
also from this cafe, which was a
rendezvous

43:06.050 --> 43:07.685 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
for traffickers and their
clients.

43:07.718 --> 43:14.158 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The Syrians are doing what's
necessary to
survive on the wrong side of the
tracks.

43:14.192 --> 43:19.530 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Many of their children work in
leather or
textile sweatshops.

43:19.564 --> 43:24.268 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
These young Syrians were on a
lunch break
from a textile factory and would
only confirm

43:24.302 --> 43:27.405 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
they have been working for
years, despite
being underage.

43:27.438 --> 43:33.845 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Under new Turkish laws, Syrian
children with
identity papers are allowed to
attend state

43:33.878 --> 43:35.613 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
schools.

43:35.646 --> 43:40.651 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But aid agencies estimate that
only 5,000
out of 22,000 eligible children
in the Izmir

43:40.685 --> 43:42.520 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
area have taken up that right.

43:42.553 --> 43:45.122 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
The rest are believed to be
working.

43:45.156 --> 43:48.960 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Mohammed Sali Ali founded a
charity to help
Syrian refugees.

43:48.993 --> 43:52.630 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MOHAMMED SALI ALI, Charity
Founder (through
translator): When the parents
fled Syrian,

43:52.663 --> 43:54.198 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
they had some money in their
pockets.

43:54.232 --> 43:56.334 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But, after a few months, they
ran out of money.

43:56.367 --> 43:57.735 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
They don't have any income.

43:57.768 --> 43:59.303 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They don't have any work or
trade.

43:59.337 --> 44:02.573 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So they had to choose between
begging and
sending the kids to work.

44:02.607 --> 44:06.777 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MALCOLM BRABANT: Turkey is
hosting more refugees
than any other country.

44:06.811 --> 44:09.780 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Aid agencies warn of growing
racial tension.

44:09.814 --> 44:13.985 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And in the back streets of
Izmir, there's
clear resentment from Turks
about the impact

44:14.018 --> 44:19.390 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
refugees have on the labor
market, at a time
when there's 12 percent
unemployment nationally,

44:19.423 --> 44:21.158 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
a seven-year high.

44:21.192 --> 44:24.629 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
OMER YESHIL, Turkey (through
translator):
The Turks should first think
about their own

44:24.662 --> 44:25.630 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
people.

44:25.663 --> 44:26.664 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Retired people are starving.

44:26.697 --> 44:28.933 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I can't even find work with the
minimum wage.

44:28.966 --> 44:31.802 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We, as Turkish citizens, can
hardly make a
living.

44:31.836 --> 44:33.070 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Do you understand?

44:33.104 --> 44:34.906 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We are worse off than the
Syrians.

44:34.939 --> 44:38.709 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ADNAN KIRBY, Turkey (through
translator):
At the moment, because the
Syrians' employment

44:38.743 --> 44:40.745 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
went down a lot, they work on
the cheap.

44:40.778 --> 44:45.483 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And because they work for low
wages, the situation
for Turkish workers is bad now.

44:45.516 --> 44:48.753 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MAN (through translator): They
are our guests
here.

44:48.786 --> 44:50.254 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Why should we complain?

44:50.288 --> 44:53.991 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
One day, when things are OK
again in their
own land, they will go back.

44:54.025 --> 44:58.963 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MALCOLM BRABANT: But Zahir
Bhatah is planning
to stay, along with his
4-year-old autistic

44:58.996 --> 44:59.964 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
son, Anver.

44:59.997 --> 45:02.733 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
He didn't dare take a rubber
dingy to Greece.

45:02.767 --> 45:05.403 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ZAHIR BHATAH, Syrian Refugee:
The sea is very
dangerous.

45:05.436 --> 45:07.004 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
My son is very small.

45:07.038 --> 45:09.340 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
And he cannot swim.

45:09.373 --> 45:13.611 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I have many friends who drowned
in the sea.

45:13.644 --> 45:18.783 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So I am get so scared to travel
to Europe.

45:18.816 --> 45:22.954 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
So I decided to stay in Izmir.

45:22.987 --> 45:28.426 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MALCOLM BRABANT: Bhatah used to
be a heart
surgeon in Damascus.

45:28.459 --> 45:30.928 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
In Izmir, he worked as a baker
for a while.

45:30.962 --> 45:34.732 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He's applying for Turkish
citizenship under
President Erdogan's new
initiative.

45:34.765 --> 45:43.541 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ZAHIR BHATAH: I think it's
better for me to
find a chance to work as a
doctor in Turkey.

45:43.574 --> 45:49.113 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MALCOLM BRABANT: Other refugees
are taking
Turkish lessons to improve their
chances of

45:49.146 --> 45:52.183 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
assimilation and employment.

45:52.216 --> 45:56.687 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Last year, at Ramadan, the
Turkish president
promised citizenship for all
refugees from

45:56.721 --> 46:01.525 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Syria and Iraq, but had to
retreat because
of widespread opposition.

46:01.559 --> 46:06.330 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now an aid group called Bridging
People says
that Turks should remember what
happened to

46:06.364 --> 46:11.102 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
hundreds of thousands of theirs
countrymen
when they migrated to Germany
for work after

46:11.135 --> 46:12.770 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
the Second World War.

46:12.803 --> 46:17.708 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Burcu Senturk, a spokeswoman for
Bridging
People, argues that Turkey
should copy the

46:17.742 --> 46:19.910 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Germans and grant the Syrians
citizenship.

46:19.944 --> 46:23.014 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BURCU SENTURK, Bridging People:
When they
come here, they are not
refugees.

46:23.047 --> 46:25.316 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They are people with their
families and hopes.

46:25.349 --> 46:30.154 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I think, in due time, they
will be settling
down in Turkey with their unique
stories and

46:30.187 --> 46:31.555 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
unique qualifications.

46:31.589 --> 46:34.558 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And this is why we need to
embrace all of
them.

46:34.592 --> 46:38.229 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MALCOLM BRABANT: Senturk argues
that Turks
will benefit from such a
proposal.

46:38.262 --> 46:42.967 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BURCU SENTURK: I think that this
will protect
many Syrians and other nations'
refugees in

46:43.000 --> 46:45.202 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Turkey if they become citizens.

46:45.236 --> 46:50.508 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And since the Turkish workers
and the other
nationalities' workers will be
working in

46:50.541 --> 46:56.480 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the same conditions, it will
also decrease
the potential for racism and
violence between

46:56.514 --> 46:58.215 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
the people.

46:58.249 --> 47:01.118 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MALCOLM BRABANT: While the
president may be
sympathetic, campaigners say
they need to

47:01.152 --> 47:06.357 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
convince lawmakers from the
ruling party that
the alternative to citizenship
is potential

47:06.390 --> 47:12.797 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
strife in the future from
stateless disenfranchised
people, especially the young,
like the 8-year-old

47:12.830 --> 47:17.368 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
who says he was clawed by a
Turkish teacher.

47:17.401 --> 47:24.175 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Children selling tissues, the
underage fruit-picker
banned from playing soccer on a
farmer's land,

47:24.208 --> 47:26.343 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
they face an uncertain future.

47:26.377 --> 47:32.516 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
But the heart surgeon is
optimistic that his
hosts will judge that his skills
are worth

47:32.550 --> 47:35.252 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
harnessing and make him a Turk.

47:35.286 --> 47:39.690 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
For the "PBS NewsHour," I'm
Malcolm Brabant
in Izmir.

47:39.724 --> 47:52.536 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Now: a most
unusual take on
ghost stories, Abraham Lincoln,
and the dead.

47:52.570 --> 47:55.639 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Jeffrey Brown has this latest
addition to
the "NewsHour" Bookshelf.

47:55.673 --> 48:01.378 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: February 20,
1862, 12-year
old Willie Lincoln has just died
of typhoid

48:01.412 --> 48:05.382 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and been interred at Oak Hills
Cemetery in
Washington, D.C.

48:05.416 --> 48:08.452 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
His grieving father, the
president, visits
at night.

48:08.486 --> 48:10.254 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
So far, all true.

48:10.287 --> 48:15.092 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But in the new novel "Lincoln in
the Bardo,"
it's the cemetery's ghostly
inhabitants that

48:15.126 --> 48:17.862 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
tell us of the visit and its
consequences.

48:17.895 --> 48:22.266 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
This is the first novel by
George Saunders,
widely acclaimed as a short
story writer,

48:22.299 --> 48:25.736 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
including his most recent
collection, "Tenth
of December."

48:25.770 --> 48:26.737 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
And welcome to you.

48:26.771 --> 48:28.439 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Nice to see you again.

48:28.472 --> 48:29.874 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
GEORGE SAUNDERS, Author,
"Lincoln in the Bardo":
Nice to be here, nice to be
here.

48:29.907 --> 48:30.741 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: So, this is a
ghost story,
very human ghosts, right?

48:30.775 --> 48:32.877 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They don't even think they're
stuck.

48:32.910 --> 48:33.878 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They don't even know they're
stuck.

48:33.911 --> 48:34.879 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They don't even know they're
dead.

48:34.912 --> 48:36.680 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
GEORGE SAUNDERS: They don't even
know yet.

48:36.714 --> 48:39.517 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Yes, they're stuck, and they're
stuck kind
of in the condition they were in
at the moment

48:39.550 --> 48:41.318 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
of death.

48:41.352 --> 48:45.723 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, if they were worried about
something or
feeling shortchanged or in love
or in hate,

48:45.756 --> 48:49.994 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
they suddenly are in this other
place, and
desperately trying to stay
there, which they

48:50.027 --> 48:51.395 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
do by repeating their
grievances.

48:51.428 --> 48:53.697 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Which makes them
very, very
human, very, very alive.

48:53.731 --> 48:56.801 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GEORGE SAUNDERS: They're just
neurotic and
free-floating, yes.

48:56.834 --> 49:00.471 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: We should say the
bardo is
a Tibetan term for a transition?

49:00.504 --> 49:02.239 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GEORGE SAUNDERS: Well, actually,
we're in
one now.

49:02.273 --> 49:04.175 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We're in the transition between
birth and
death.

49:04.208 --> 49:08.279 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But the one that people often
know about is
the transition between the
moment of death

49:08.312 --> 49:11.215 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and whatever comes next, so
reincarnation
or heaven or hell.

49:11.248 --> 49:15.152 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: So, this
particular bardo is
a cemetery, as I said, a real
one, not too

49:15.186 --> 49:17.655 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
far from here in Washington,
D.C., right?

49:17.688 --> 49:21.926 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And you tell the story through
voices, a chorus
of voices.

49:21.959 --> 49:23.661 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Why that approach?

49:23.694 --> 49:28.432 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GEORGE SAUNDERS: The first thing
I wanted
to not do was tell it in a way
that made death

49:28.465 --> 49:31.468 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and this experience seem banal
or manageable.

49:31.502 --> 49:35.806 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, my approach to fiction is to
kind of just
to go in there moment by moment
and try to

49:35.840 --> 49:37.575 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
always make some sparks.

49:37.608 --> 49:41.045 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, in this case, it meant kind
of telling
it from a strange angle that
might even give

49:41.078 --> 49:44.682 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the reader a little struggle in
the first
10 to 15 pages.

49:44.715 --> 49:48.519 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
But I thought, you know,
whatever happens
after this life, it would be
really strange

49:48.552 --> 49:49.653 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
if it was what we expected.

49:49.687 --> 49:51.789 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, I wanted to kind of simulate
that in the
book.

49:51.822 --> 49:56.427 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So the reader is a little
destabilized, the
ghosts are a little
destabilized, and I found

49:56.460 --> 49:58.262 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
you could kind of do that
through the form
of the thing.

49:58.295 --> 50:01.332 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Just to make it
clear to our
audience, there's no one
narrator.

50:01.365 --> 50:07.671 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's all of these voices which
you are assembling,
including snippets from and
quotations from

50:07.705 --> 50:10.174 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
real historians and some made-up
historians.

50:10.207 --> 50:12.009 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
GEORGE SAUNDERS: Right.

50:12.042 --> 50:15.212 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
When I first heard the story
about Lincoln,
I -- it was so beautiful to me
and sorrowful

50:15.246 --> 50:21.118 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and gorgeous, that I -- my
mantra was kind
of just make the ending so --
make the book

50:21.151 --> 50:25.422 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
so weird and beautiful, that it
would do some
justice to that emotional core.

50:25.456 --> 50:29.360 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, along the way, that was a
great mantra
to kind of say, does this
decision lead to

50:29.393 --> 50:31.929 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the direction of emotional power
or not?

50:31.962 --> 50:35.733 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so the strange thing was,
following those
bread crumbs, I looked up about
a third of

50:35.766 --> 50:40.537 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the way in, and it had this
crazy form, and
very fun and gratifying.

50:40.571 --> 50:45.075 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: It raised the
question for
me just about, almost, what is a
novel?

50:45.109 --> 50:48.145 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GEORGE SAUNDERS: Well, somebody
told me is
a novel is a long work of prose
that has something

50:48.178 --> 50:49.146 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
wrong with it.

50:49.179 --> 50:50.681 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
So, I think, by that...

50:50.714 --> 50:51.682 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

50:51.715 --> 50:52.683 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
GEORGE SAUNDERS: ... standard,
it qualifies.

50:52.716 --> 50:53.684 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I never -- I wanted to write a
novel.

50:53.717 --> 50:55.686 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
This particular material was so
insistent.

50:55.719 --> 50:59.523 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I really kept a close eye on
it, like,
don't be a novel unless you have
to.

50:59.556 --> 51:02.826 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And at some point, it really
convinced me
that it deserved the length.

51:02.860 --> 51:07.831 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: And it makes me
wonder, did
you feel you had to sort of play
with the

51:07.865 --> 51:11.068 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
form of a novel, or you -- you
just couldn't
write a straightforward
narrative?

51:11.101 --> 51:13.437 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GEORGE SAUNDERS: I couldn't
write a straightforward
narrative.

51:13.470 --> 51:15.873 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And I couldn't write a brief
narrative.

51:15.906 --> 51:17.107 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
But, again, I would have.

51:17.141 --> 51:18.342 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I have been happy to do all of
that.

51:18.375 --> 51:20.377 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
But it's kind of strange.

51:20.411 --> 51:23.714 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
My artistic approach is that
you're supposed
to be a little baffled as you're
writing.

51:23.747 --> 51:24.715 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
And...

51:24.748 --> 51:25.716 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: You, the writer?

51:25.749 --> 51:27.117 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
GEORGE SAUNDERS: Yes.

51:27.151 --> 51:28.852 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The holiest state is to be a
little confused
about what you're doing.

51:28.886 --> 51:33.891 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And you're guiding by the energy
that the
story is actually giving you as
you revise.

51:33.924 --> 51:38.495 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That's kind of tricky, because
it means you
have to abandon your ideas about
organization

51:38.529 --> 51:43.534 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
or thematics, and really submit
to the story,
just as if it was a friend kind
of trying

51:43.567 --> 51:45.336 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
to convince you of something.

51:45.369 --> 51:49.573 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, if you do that, sometimes,
it takes you
-- it asks you to do really
crazy things.

51:49.606 --> 51:52.509 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And, for me, that's the thrill
of it, is to
say, OK, I will try it.

51:52.543 --> 51:55.346 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And then, hopefully, it will
result in some
kind of new mode of beauty.

51:55.379 --> 51:58.582 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: And, at some
point, you're
no longer confused by what
you're doing?

51:58.615 --> 52:00.417 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
It never stops?

52:00.451 --> 52:02.753 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GEORGE SAUNDERS: I'm still
confused, because,
hopefully, the book is doing
things that you

52:02.786 --> 52:04.521 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
didn't consciously plan.

52:04.555 --> 52:09.460 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: So, at the core
of this is
this figure, Abraham Lincoln,
probably the

52:09.493 --> 52:13.564 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
most written of personage in
American history,
right?

52:13.597 --> 52:19.103 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You come at him through angles,
the voices
of the ghosts observing him, his
son, the

52:19.136 --> 52:20.637 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
historians.

52:20.671 --> 52:25.042 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Was that because you couldn't
get a grasp
of him, or you didn't want to?

52:25.075 --> 52:26.910 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
GEORGE SAUNDERS: It scared me to
try.

52:26.944 --> 52:31.915 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, also, I was a little bit
afraid of coming
with all that conventional
wisdom about him.

52:31.949 --> 52:35.419 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, at one point, I thought,
you know, actually,
I don't want to write a book
about Lincoln.

52:35.452 --> 52:39.923 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There's -- I don't claim to know
him, but
I needed him, the father who's
so grief-stricken,

52:39.957 --> 52:41.925 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
he goes to see his dead son's
body.

52:41.959 --> 52:46.296 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: This is Abraham
Lincoln at
a moment of tremendous personal
grief, but

52:46.330 --> 52:50.968 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
also surrounded by the Civil War
and the grief
of so many who will die, right?

52:51.001 --> 52:51.969 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
GEORGE SAUNDERS: Yes.

52:52.002 --> 52:53.470 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Right, right.

52:53.504 --> 52:55.506 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It was actually a wonderful
chance to hang
out with him for four years.

52:55.539 --> 53:01.345 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You see a president who really
made a virtue
of things like sorrow, of being
defeated,

53:01.378 --> 53:03.113 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
because he had setback after
setback.

53:03.147 --> 53:04.948 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
He has this great loss.

53:04.982 --> 53:10.854 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, somehow, he was able to
transform all
that sorrow into a kind of
expanding empathy

53:10.888 --> 53:12.723 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
for everybody, you know?

53:12.756 --> 53:17.194 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It was kind of inspiring to see
somebody whose
response to fear or hardship was
expansiveness,

53:17.227 --> 53:18.429 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
instead of shrinkage.

53:18.462 --> 53:20.798 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: The new novel is
"Lincoln in
the Bardo."

53:20.831 --> 53:25.636 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
George Saunders, thank you very
much.

53:25.669 --> 53:30.874 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
GEORGE SAUNDERS: Thank you so
